# Normalize all text to LF in every working tree, on every platform.
# Several tests compare a committed file byte-for-byte against generated output
# that uses `\n` only (the descriptor golden snapshot and the committed JSON
# schema, embedded via include_str!). Windows CI runners default
# core.autocrlf=true, which would otherwise check those out as CRLF and break the
# compare. Pinning eol=lf makes the build platform-independent.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Binary assets — never touch their bytes.
*.tosc binary
*.wav binary
# The vendored tokenizer vocab is base64 text, but it is hash-pinned to an exact byte sequence
# (eval/reuben_eval/tokenizer/pins.json) and the eval gate refuses to run if a byte moves. Mark it
# binary so no eol/`text=auto` normalization can ever touch it and break the pin. It is committed
# plainly, NOT via LFS: 1.6 MB, frozen since 2022, written once and never rewritten — LFS would add
# CI/contributor friction and a new gate-break mode (an unfetched pointer stub failing the hash) for
# no benefit the sha256 pin doesn't already give. see rules: agent-mcp
*.tiktoken binary
